node.text: A true pioneer in both underwater filmmaking and shark research, Valerie Taylor is a living legend whose life’s work has become the basis for much of what we know about sharks today. Follow this daring ocean explorer’s trajectory from champion spearfisher to passionate shark protector in Playing With Sharks, now streaming on @disneyplus

node.text: Rio De Janeiro, Brazil: Witness the inspiring story of Tuany, a 23-year-old ballet dancer who started a dance company for young girls in the middle of one of Rio De Janeiro’s most dangerous favelas. She gives students hope for a better future and a safe space away from the violent world around them.

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text: Half Moon Bay, California, U.S.A.: Kelsey is driven by two passions: surfing and helping people through grief and trauma. Photo by David Guttenfelder @dguttenfelder / Inside Sean Sherman's Indigenous Food Lab in Minneapolis, chefs prepare duck to be distributed to elders in Indigenous communities in need across Minnesota. As 1 in 8 go hungry in the state, restaurants and food banks have banded together to salvage jobs—and served over a million meals.

Sherman and his group, aka the Sioux Chef, cook with ingredients available to Indigenous people in pre-colonial times. They offered about 36,000 meals in November and December alone, when Minnesota’s food industry shifted gears to feed the most vulnerable. 

Across the U.S., the pandemic left record numbers of people without enough food. For many, charities and neighbors have become lifelines. Check out the August issue story, "America’s Hunger Crisis" at the link in our bio.

Photo by @lucasfogliaphoto / Eleanor Kuntz had stayed overnight at a friend's house in Brooklyn on September 10, 2001. After the first plane hit the World Trade Center the next day, they went up to the building's roof. "We saw the second plane hit the second tower. We didn’t really know what to do except walk toward the bridge. People were just flooding over. Women carrying their shoes. People covered in gray ash. It was raining ash and pieces of paper. It was one of the most powerful experiences of my life. You had people buying all the water in the grocery stores, bringing their shopping carts out in the street, and just handing bottles out. I had never witnessed that kind of disaster and hurt, and also an outpouring of love and care at the same time,” says Eleanor Kuntz.

This image is part of my book, Summer After, published by Stanley/Barker for the 20th anniversary of the September 11 attacks. For more, visit @lucasfogliaphoto.

node.text: Photos by Muhammed Muheisen @mmuheisen / In March I visited the world’s first vaccine clinic in a refugee camp. The story for National Geographic was one of hope and resilience: The refugees fled Syria and live in shelters—but there’s a vaccine for them. Jordan was one of the first countries to vaccinate refugees, at the Zaatari refugee camp, seen here. I'm proud of Jordan, I have to say. All these people who fled war and now face a pandemic are going to have a second chance. Also in this carousel: a health worker runs a  temperature check on Fatimah, a 64-year-old Syrian refugee; Adnan, a 58-year-old Syrian refugee from Daraa, receives his second dose of a vaccine; fully vaccinated Zahra, a 111-year-old Syrian refugee; and bicycles and a donkey-pulled wagon inside the camp. For more photos and videos of the refugee crisis, follow me @mmuheisen @mmuheisenpublic. For more on how to get involved, follow @everydayrefugees. #muhammedmuheisen #everydayrefugees

node.text: Photos by Stephen Alvarez @salvarezphoto / Dirk Hoffman looks at an engraving of an auroch (Bos primigenius) in Spain's El Castillo cave. The auroch was a species of large, wild cattle that once roamed Europe and Asia. Cave art is full of surprises, like images of extinct animals. One of the most startling finds by Hoffman in El Castillo is that some of the art is far older than  once assumed. He and his collaborators established that the first images were painted in this cave over 40,000 years ago. Their later studies suggest that some art in Spanish caves may have been made by Neanderthals. Ancient images like this engraving reveal much about our prehistory. Sharing and preserving them led me to start the nonprofit @ancientartarchive. Follow me @salvarezphoto and @ancientartarchive for more.

Video by @bertiegregory / Wait for it! This is a huge basking shark (they’re all big, but this female was a real biggie). Wildlife producer Chadden Hunter once described a shot he wanted me to get: the Millennium Falcon Star Wars shot, where you get under a subject with your back to it, and then get it entering the frame over the top of you. (That's a technique used in the Star Wars movies to make spaceships look epic). Having failed to get this shot on several shoots with anacondas and beluga whales, it suddenly came to mind when I was in the water with these sharks. But I was free diving, and getting into position for this shot takes a lot of kicking and a big breath-hold. Once in position, I had to trust that I’d lined up right, and then just wait with my back to the shark. Being a plankton eater, it’s not going to bite off my head, but it’s still a chunky animal. After a few days of trying, I finally managed to get this shark lined up correctly. Fortunately, she was a huge individual, so the shot looked great! Unfortunately, because she was a huge individual, she took a long time to pass. Eventually her almost eight-meter (25 ft) body passed overhead—and I could go to the surface. That first breath felt really good! Follow @bertiegregory for more wildlife adventures. 
#britishwildlife #underwater #freediving #baskingshark #shark #scotland

Photo by @michaelchristopherbrown / Cubans in the province of Camaguey watch the military convoy transporting Fidel Castro's ashes from Havana to Santiago in December 2016. As night fell, we passed through the rural Camaguey. People stood in the rain, some barefoot and most without umbrellas, cheering, saluting, or patiently waiting. There were few streetlights, so to photograph I relied on the headlights of taxis behind and in front of us. 

Fidel came to power in 1959, and died on November 25, 2016. He was 90. His ashes were taken to Santa Ifigenia Cemetery, where his brother Raúl placed the urn inside a giant boulder and behind a marble plaque with “Fidel” on it, next to where the Cuban independence hero José Martí is buried. Follow @michaelchristopherbrown for more human stories from around the world.

node.text: Video by @joelsartore / The Pampas cat is predominantly nocturnal, waiting to go on the prowl until it's safely masked by the cover of darkness. While they spend most of their time on the ground, the cats are skilled climbers, opting to rest in the trees. Little is known about the social structure of the Pampas cat, or how they communicate with one another, but some individuals have been observed erecting the hair along their spines when excited. Video taken @ufas_unab. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark follow me, @joelsartore. #cat #kitten #pampascat #colocolo #clown #feline #female #PhotoArk

Photo by @thomaspeschak / The best camera/lens combination is often simply the one you're holding in your hands! I was walking through coastal forest on the tiny Seychelles island of Cousine when a white tern began to hover inches from my face—and tried to land on my head. Unfortunately, I was on my way to go diving, so in addition to wearing a wet suit and clutching my fins in my teeth, I was holding my bulky underwater camera setup. With no other option than the gear in my hands, I raised my underwater rig to my eye, framed as best I could, and hit the shutter. Follow @thomaspeschak for more photographs from the Seychelles and other Indian Ocean islands. 
#seychelles #islandlife #birdsofinstagram #seabirds #indianocean

node.text: Photo by @kiliiiyuyan / A Yurok tribal member and firefighter manages the boundary of a prescribed burn in Northern California, in a program known as TREX. With wildfires raging in California in recent years, Indigenous fire practices have come to the fore. Indigenous prescribed burning—an art over 13,000 years old—is thought to have kept destructive wildfires at bay for millennia by burning away small sections of "forest fuel" during cooler, controlled conditions. The benefits include promotion of oak woodlands, increased deer and game populations, and even cooler water for spawning salmon. Today such Indigenous management processes are being elevated as potent tools for biodiversity and conservation. #indigenous #culturalfire #california
